---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Lutaro — Camera Setup Guide"
  description="How to set up your Sony camera for Lutaro: Wi-Fi, connecting away from home, PC Remote, Access Authentication, pairing, and USB — with exact menu paths for both menu generations."
>
  <h1>Set up your Sony camera for Lutaro</h1>
  <p class="meta">Menu paths verified against Sony's official α6700 Help Guide · July 2026</p>

  <p>
    Lutaro talks to your camera the same way Sony's own remote software does:
    over Wi-Fi using the camera's <strong>PC Remote</strong> function, or (on
    Mac) over USB. This guide walks through every camera setting the app
    needs, with the exact menu paths.
  </p>

  <div class="note">
    <strong>Two menu generations.</strong> Newer Sony bodies (a9&nbsp;III,
    α1&nbsp;II, ZV-E1, and recent firmware on the a7&nbsp;IV, a7R&nbsp;V, and
    α1) renamed the remote-control menus:
    <em>Cnct./PC&nbsp;Remote → PC&nbsp;Remote Function</em> became
    <em>Cnct./Remote&nbsp;Sht. → Remote Shoot Function</em>. The α6700 and
    most earlier bodies keep the classic names. Both are shown below;
    everything else is named the same on both generations.
  </div>

  <h2 id="wifi">1. Put the camera on your Wi-Fi network</h2>
  <p>
    Camera and device (iPhone, iPad, or Mac) must be on the same Wi-Fi
    network.
  </p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Wi-Fi → Wi-Fi Connect = On</span>
  <p>
    The camera searches for access points. If yours isn't listed, use
    <strong>WPS Push</strong> (press the WPS button on your router) or
    <strong>Access Point Set.</strong> (enter the network name and password
    manually) in the same Wi-Fi menu.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    Recent firmware (α6700 2.00 and later) supports only WPA2/WPA3 networks —
    the camera won't join old WPA- or WEP-secured networks.
  </div>

  <h2 id="away-from-home">2. Connecting away from home</h2>
  <p>
    No router to join? When the camera and your iPhone can't share a Wi-Fi
    network, Lutaro can still find the camera over two field-friendly
    connections, with manual IP entry as a universal fallback.
  </p>

  <h3>Camera as its own access point</h3>
  <p>Turn the camera into a Wi-Fi access point and join it directly:</p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Cnct./PC Remote → PC Remote Function → Wi-Fi Direct Info</span>
  <p>
    Set the connection method to <strong>access point</strong>, then join
    that network from your iPhone's Wi-Fi settings. The camera is always at
    <strong>192.168.122.1</strong> in this mode.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    Lutaro finds the camera automatically in this mode as of the release
    with the away-from-home scan fix. On an older version, enter
    <strong>192.168.122.1</strong> manually (see below).
  </div>

  <h3>iPhone Personal Hotspot</h3>
  <p>
    Turn on Personal Hotspot on your iPhone and keep the Personal Hotspot
    screen open so the camera can find it, then join it from the camera:
  </p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Wi-Fi → Access Point Set.</span>
  <p>
    Default iPhone hotspot settings work as-is on the α6700 — no special
    configuration needed.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    <strong>Camera can't see the hotspot?</strong> Set
    <span class="path">MENU → Network → Wi-Fi → Wi-Fi Frequency Band</span>
    to 2.4&nbsp;GHz on the camera. On iPhones that offer it, also try
    <em>Maximize Compatibility</em> in the Personal Hotspot settings.
  </div>

  <h3>Manual IP entry</h3>
  <p>
    Works in any connection mode, and is the fallback if a scan doesn't find
    the camera. In camera-as-access-point mode the address is always
    <strong>192.168.122.1</strong>; on a hotspot or shared Wi-Fi network,
    check the camera's own network settings screen for its current IP
    address, then enter it in Lutaro under
    <strong>Enter IP Manually</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="pc-remote">3. Turn on PC Remote</h2>
  <p>This is the switch that lets Lutaro connect at all.</p>
  <div class="overflow">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Bodies</th><th>Menu path</th></tr>
      <tr>
        <td>α6700 and most earlier bodies</td>
        <td>MENU → Network → Cnct./PC Remote → PC Remote Function →
            PC Remote = <strong>On</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>a9 III, α1 II, ZV-E1, updated a7 IV / a7R V / α1</td>
        <td>MENU → Network → Cnct./Remote Sht. → Remote Shoot Function →
            Remote Shooting = <strong>On</strong></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>
  <div class="note">
    The camera drops Wi-Fi when it sleeps. If Lutaro can't find it, wake the
    camera (half-press the shutter) and scan again.
  </div>

  <h2 id="access-auth">4. Access Authentication — with or without a password</h2>
  <p>
    Sony cameras can protect remote connections with a user name and
    password. The setting is called <strong>Access Authen.</strong> and lives
    in the same place on both menu generations:
  </p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Network Option → Access Authen. Settings → Access Authen.</span>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>On</strong> — the connection is authenticated and encrypted
      (SSH). Lutaro asks for the camera's user name and password. This is
      Sony's recommended mode.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Off</strong> — no password, no encryption; instead the camera
      asks you to approve each new device once (<a href="#pairing">pairing</a>,
      below). Sony's help guide warns the connection can be intercepted in
      this mode.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Where to find the user name and password</h3>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Network Option → Access Authen. Info</span>
  <p>
    This screen shows the camera's user name, password, MAC address, and
    fingerprint. The credentials are auto-generated at the factory; you can
    change them (or generate a fresh password) under
    <em>Access Authen. Settings</em>. Type the user name and password into
    Lutaro exactly as shown.
  </p>
  <div class="note">
    If you regenerate the password, saved connections in Lutaro will fail
    until you enter the new one — the app will tell you when that happens.
  </div>

  <h2 id="pairing">5. Pairing (only when Access Authen. is Off)</h2>
  <p>
    With Access Authen. <strong>Off</strong>, the first connection from a new
    device must be approved on the camera body:
  </p>
  <div class="overflow">
    <table>
      <tr><th>Bodies</th><th>Menu path</th></tr>
      <tr>
        <td>α6700 and most earlier bodies</td>
        <td>MENU → Network → Cnct./PC Remote → PC Remote Function → Pairing</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>a9 III, α1 II, ZV-E1, updated a7 IV / a7R V / α1</td>
        <td>MENU → Network → Cnct./Remote Sht. → Remote Shoot Function → Pairing</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
  </div>
  <ol>
    <li>Open <em>Pairing</em> on the camera.</li>
    <li>Connect from Lutaro.</li>
    <li>Approve the prompt that appears on the camera screen.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The camera remembers up to 20 paired devices. If the list fills up (or
    after a camera initialization), clear it and re-pair:
  </p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Network → Network Option → Reset Network Set.</span>
  <div class="note">
    Reset Network Set. clears <em>all</em> network settings, including saved
    Wi-Fi networks — you'll need step 1 again afterwards.
  </div>

  <h2 id="usb">6. USB (Mac only)</h2>
  <p>
    On the Mac, Lutaro can also connect over a USB cable. Set the camera's
    USB mode to remote control:
  </p>
  <span class="path">MENU → Setup → USB → USB Connection Mode → PC Remote</span>
  <p>
    If USB Connection Mode is set to <em>Sel. When Connect</em>, the camera
    asks on every cable connect — choose
    <strong>Remote Shoot (PC Remote)</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2 id="troubleshooting">7. Troubleshooting</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Camera not found on Wi-Fi</strong> — it's probably asleep; the
      camera drops Wi-Fi when idle. Wake it, confirm it's on the same network,
      and confirm PC Remote (step 3) is On.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Scan finds nothing away from home</strong> — with no local
      network, Lutaro shows a "No Local Network" screen and still checks any
      recently-connected camera. To connect, use one of the three options
      above: <a href="#away-from-home">camera-as-access-point, Personal
      Hotspot, or manual IP entry</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>"Camera is busy"</strong> — another app holds the connection.
      Close Imaging Edge Desktop, Creators' App, or any other Sony remote
      software, then retry. Sony cameras allow only one remote session at a
      time.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Wrong user name or password</strong> — re-check them on the
      camera under <em>Network → Network Option → Access Authen. Info</em>.
      They're case-sensitive.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>"Fingerprint changed"</strong> — appears after a camera
      initialization or network reset, or if a different camera answers at
      the same address. If you reset the camera (or this is genuinely a
      different body), trust the new fingerprint; otherwise check your
      network.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Pairing prompt never appears</strong> — make sure the camera is
      sitting in the <em>Pairing</em> menu (step 5) <em>before</em> you
      connect from Lutaro.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="support">Questions?</h2>
  <p>
    Open an issue at
    <a href="https://github.com/tarakanof/Lutaro-Site/issues">github.com/tarakanof/Lutaro-Site/issues</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 3rem; font-size: 0.85em;">
    Menu names are Sony's; paths were verified against the official
    <a href="https://helpguide.sony.net/ilc/2320/v1/en/">α6700 Help Guide</a>
    (and the a9&nbsp;III / α1&nbsp;II / ZV-E1 guides for the newer naming) in
    July 2026. Sony may rename menus in future firmware — if a path doesn't
    match your camera, check the
    <a href="https://www.sony.net/electronics/support/">help guide for your
    model</a>.
  </p>
</Base>
